          <p class="lead">
            It has been over 3 years since a catastrophic earthquake struck Haiti on 12 January 2010. The 7.0 magnitude earthquake struck less than 20 miles from Haitian capital of Port-au-Prince, killing 300,000 people and leaving the surrounding area in ruin. Many countries, organizations, and individuals quickly rushed to help Haiti, but the scene was already set. Haiti has faced a difficult to road to recovery. In the aftermath of the earthquake, cholera broke out. Because of the lack of clean water cholera has spread like wildfire since it first appeared about 10 months after the earthquake. Since then it has killed over 7,000 Haitians and over half a million have fallen ill to disease. As the rainy season approaches, the number of cases per month is expected to increase by more than double. In remote areas of the country, small groups of doctors and nurses make slow and difficult treks to track the disease and help those afflicted by it. For the doctors and nurses fighting the disease, the sharing of data is a matter of life and death.
            <br><br>
            The first goal of OASIS-Haiti is to aid medical and public health organizations to eradicate cholera. We plan to help epidemiologists in tracking and visualizing the presence of cholera through the use of KEEP and geospatial visualizations. Distributed Health Labs will also work on enhancing its SENSE device to test for organic contaminants, like viruses and bacterias. If low-cost assay technologies like those used being used in OASIS-Mongolia can be adapted to work with SENSE, then Haitians everywhere will have a low-cost testing tool and be able to contribute to eradication efforts by regularly testing their own drinking water sources.
          </p>
